ll and then we are reborn\n\n- Micheline\n|\nWhen life goes, the body becomes weaker\n\n- Sunday\n|\nThere are no environments where you're only going to win, because life just isn't like that.\n\n- Bobby\n|\nDining with the King; your attire, attitude and mentality must change.\n\n- Jaachynma N.E. Agu, Risk It, Be Different\n|\nFor one wild, glad moment we snapped the chain that binds us to earth, and joining hands with the winds we felt ourselves divine.\n\n- Helen Keller, The Story of My Life\n|\nIn appearance, the worldly life looks attractive, but once you enter into it, you can never become free.\n\n- Dada\n|\nGod is the supreme uncreated light of which Wisdom is born, but there was never a time when God's Wisdom did not exist.\n\n- Merritt Y. Hughes, Ten Perspectives on Milton\n|\nTo talk well and eloquently is a very great art, but that an equally great one is to know the right moment to stop.\n\n- Wolfgang\n|\nGood books are for consideration after, too.\n\n- Stephen King, Hearts in Atlantis\n|\nPoems are a hotline to our hearts, and we forget this emotional power at our peril.\n\n- Andrew\n|\nThis feather stirs; she lives! if it be so, it is a chance which does redeem all sorrows that ever I have felt.\n\n- William Shakespeare, King Lear\n|\nEducation is liberation, knowledge is power.\n\n- Henry\n|\nIf you formulate your question properly, mathematics gives you the answer\n\n- Savas\n|\nYou know, you're rather amusingly wrong.\n\n- Terry Pratchett, Maskerade\n|\nYour calling is in what you read, think and talk about\n\n- Sunday\n|\nBut I always liked side-paths, little dark back-alleys behind the main road- there one finds adventures and surprises, and precious metal in the dirt.\n\n- Fyodor Dostoyevsky, The Brothers Karamazov\n|\nPoetry is not an art, it's a symptom.\n\n- Michele\n|\nBecause of the Dharma, my mind was more free in prison than worldly people experience in the best of circumstances.\n\n- Yangthang\n|\nLife is all about practicing for heaven.' p 101.\n\n- Richard Rohr, Falling Upward: A Spirituality for the Two Halves of Life\n|\nWhy did I hope we would be happy abroad? A change of environment is that traditional fallacy upon which doomed loves, and lungs, rely.\n\n- Vladimir\n|\nI'm always amazed that people will stand around books for hours and only look at the spine. I think I should write a book called 'the power of having a spine' - #metaphor\n\n- Richie\n|\nYou will always think that you cant do it, you may think that the idea you have is useless, but the idea you only have can change your life.\n\n- Neymat\n|\nA constitution, as important as it is, will mean nothing unless the people are yearning for liberty and freedom.\n\n- U.S.\n|\nPeople move around so much in the world, things get lost.\n\n- Emma Donoghue, Room\n|\nBooks are love letters (or apologies) passed between us, adding a layer of conversation beyond our spoken words.\n\n- Donalyn Miller, The Book Whisperer: Awakening the Inner Reader in Every Child\n|\nTo enjoy it again and again in those moments of joy and despair, I carry the beauty of your love in the hidden chamber of my heart.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nReaders, censors know, are defined by the books they read.\n\n- Alberto Manguel, The Library at Night\n|\nMy desire is to embrace, to explore, to dance, to hug, to inspire, to know, to learn, to love, to read, to search, to seek, to share, to write……!\n\n- Lailah\n|\nI must write now and quickly, before I begin to prefer the perfect version that lives in my head.\n\n- Lettie\n|\nThere are so many things that demand to be said. Where did you go? Do you ever think about me? You've ruined me. Are you okay? But of course, I can't say any of that.\n\n- Gayle Forman, Where She Went\n|\nIt’s a truth I love you,It’s a hope you do,And may I live and die with it,Not knowing that you don’t.\n\n- Amit\n|\nIt’s fascinating. You know all these words, and they’re all English, but when you string them together into sentences, they just don’t make any 