ture and the partisans of 'goo.\n\n- Alan W. Watts, The Essential Alan Watts\n|\nHe is always doing something--the very best thing, the thing we ourselves would certainly choose if we knew the end from the beginning. He is at work to bring us to our full glory.\n\n- Elisabeth\n|\nNot truly living in the present moment & later regretting is like closing your eyes when a peacock is dancing, only to want to see it dance once it is gone.\n\n- RVM\n|\nPossibilities exist for you, to educate yourself, to the highest degree.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nIt is true that everyone has Problems, and it is also true that every problem has a Solution. If this is the reality of Life, then why not focus on solutions rather than Problems.\n\n- RVM\n|\nIf you reflect on death, you find the vanity of life.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nOnce you've found some joy, you never want to be without it.\n\n- Alec Baldwin, Nevertheless: A Memoir\n|\nAnd here's to the blues, the real blues— where there's a hint of hope in every cry of desperation.\n\n- David Mutti Clark, Professor Brown Shoes Teaches the Blues\n|\nTime is a player. Time is part of today, not simply a measure of its passing.\n\n- Jeanette Winterson, The World and Other Places: Stories\n|\nCutting people out of your life is easy, keeping them in is hard.\n\n- Walter Dean Myers, Slam!\n|\nSo we couldn't mingle with them, but we could eavesdrop. We got our knowledge that way--we caught it like germs.\n\n- Margaret Atwood, The Year of the Flood\n|\nUnless we have something worth dying for, Atretes, we've nothing worth living for.\n\n- Francine Rivers, A Voice in the Wind\n|\nBooks themselves need no defense. Their spokesmen come and go, their readers live and die, they remain constant.\n\n- Lawrence\n|\nTo enjoy the beauty of the world, don’t try to fit in. Try to fly out of your perceived boundaries.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nRather a thousand times the county jail than to lie under this marble figure with wings and this granite pedestal bearing the words 'pro patria.' What do they mean anyway?\n\n- Edgar\n|\nHere I am trying to live, or rather, I am trying to teach the death within me how to live.\n\n- Jean\n|\nSomewhere there must be women reading books,and talking of chicken rissoles to their cooks …(from,‘Somewhere in England’)\n\n- Virginia Graham, Consider the Years\n|\nExtrapolating from the statistical growth of the legal profession, by the year 2035 every single person in the United States will be a lawyer, including newborn infants.\n\n- Michael Crichton, State of Fear\n|\nNew knowledge enhances an ever increasing sense of our own ignorance. The more we know, the more we know we don't know. Feynman called it 'the expanding frontier of ignorance'.\n\n- Matt Baldwin, Snow rising"